410→                           A simple example of the order of a basis differing from the exact order is given by $A=\cup_{k\geq 0}(2^{2k},2^{2k+1}]$, which has order $2$ but exact order $3$.<br><br>Erdős and Graham <a href="#cite-ErGr80b-336" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('ErGr80b','336'); return false;">[ErGr80b]</a> have shown that a basis $A$ has an exact order if and only if $a_2-a_1,a_3-a_2,a_4-a_3,\ldots$ are coprime. They also proved that\[\frac{1}{4}\leq \lim_r \frac{h(r)}{r^2}\leq \frac{5}{4}.\]The best bounds known for the limit are\[\frac{1}{3}\leq \lim_r \frac{h(r)}{r^2}\leq \frac{1}{2},\]the lower bound originally due to Grekos <a href="#cite-Gr88-336" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Gr88','336'); return false;">[Gr88]</a> and the upper bound to Nash <a href="#cite-Na93-336" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Na93','336'); return false;">[Na93]</a>. Improved bounds in the lower order terms were given by Plagne <a href="#cite-Pl04-336" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Pl04','336'); return false;">[Pl04]</a>.<br><br>Erdős and Graham <a href="#cite-ErGr80b-336" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('ErGr80b','336'); return false;">[ErGr80b]</a> showed $h(2)=4$. Nash <a href="#cite-Na93-336" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Na93','336'); return false;">[Na93]</a> showed $h(3)=7$. The value of $h(4)$ is unknown, but it is known <a href="#cite-Pl04-336" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Pl04','336'); return false;">[Pl04]</a> that $10\leq h(4)\leq 11$.
